NNAAMMEE
       strsignal - return string describing signal

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ##iinncclluuddee <<ssttrriinngg..hh>>

       cchhaarr **ssttrrssiiggnnaall((iinntt _s_i_g));;

       eexxtteerrnn ccoonnsstt cchhaarr ** ccoonnsstt _s_y_s___s_i_g_l_i_s_t[[]];;

   Feature Test Macro Requirements for glibc (see ffeeaattuurree__tteesstt__mmaaccrrooss(7)):

       ssttrrssiiggnnaall():
           Since glibc 2.10:
               _XOPEN_SOURCE >= 700 || _POSIX_C_SOURCE >= 200809L
           Before glibc 2.10:
               _GNU_SOURCE

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       The ssttrrssiiggnnaall() function returns a string describing the signal number passed in the argument _s_i_g.  The string can be used only until the next call to ssttrrssiiggnnaall().

       The array _s_y_s___s_i_g_l_i_s_t holds the signal description strings indexed by signal number.  The ssttrrssiiggnnaall() function should be used if possible instead of this array.

RREETTUURRNN VVAALLUUEE
       The ssttrrssiiggnnaall() function returns the appropriate description string, or an unknown signal message if the signal number is invalid.  On some systems (but not on Linux), NULL may instead be returned for an invalid signal number.

AATTTTRRIIBBUUTTEESS
       For an explanation of the terms used in this section, see aattttrriibbuutteess(7).

